### D. Signals Rules

Use Angular Signals as the default reactive primitive. RxJS is for async streams (HTTP, WebSockets) only.

**Signal patterns:**
```typescript
// State
readonly count = signal(0);
readonly users = signal<User[]>([]);
readonly activeUser = signal<User | null>(null);

// Computed (derived — never store computed values in plain signals)
readonly userCount = computed(() => this.users().length);
readonly activeUserName = computed(() => this.activeUser()?.name ?? '—');

// Effect (side effects responding to signal changes)
constructor() {
  effect(() => {
    // runs whenever activeUser() changes
    const user = this.activeUser();
    if (user) this.trackAnalytics(user.id);
  });
}

// Mutation
addUser(user: User): void {
  this.users.update(current => [...current, user]);
}

removeUser(id: string): void {
  this.users.update(current => current.filter(u => u.id !== id));
}
```

**Rules:**
- Prefer `signal()` over `BehaviorSubject` for local UI state.
- Prefer `computed()` over storing derived values in separate signals.
- Use `effect()` for side effects (analytics, localStorage sync) — never for data derivation.
- Do not call `.set()` inside `computed()` — it causes circular dependencies.
- For async data, use a service with `toSignal(observable$)` from `@angular/core/rxjs-interop`.

